<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="191" pageId="5" pageNumber="190" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[113,1089,403,587]" pageId="5" pageNumber="190">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,251,403,427]" pageId="5" pageNumber="190">Description.</emphasis>
Body reddish brown with femora darker and tibiae blackish; antennal club black except last segment brownish on apical half; elytra each with two large yellow spots: one on humeral portion and another one on apicolateral portion. Antennae (
<figureCitation box="[869,946,467,491]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1545,1564]" captionTargetBox="[244,968,624,1523]" captionTargetId="figure-141@5.[228,972,612,1535]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 13–16. Scaphidium bituberculatum sp. nov. 13 – aedeagus; 14 – internal sac; 15 – male front leg; 16 – antenna. Scale bars: 0.25 mm (13–14); 1 mm (15–16)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5330008" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5330008/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="190">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
) with similar coloration to those in 
<taxonomicName authority="Tang &amp; Li, 2012" authorityName="Tang &amp; Li" authorityYear="2012" box="[346,468,500,523]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Scaphidium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="190" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="yinziweii" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[346,468,500,523]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="190">S. yinziweii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[474,557,500,523]" pageId="5" pageNumber="190" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[113,1089,403,587]" pageId="5" pageNumber="190">
Body measurements: BL: 7.0– 
<quantity box="[469,551,531,555]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.1" pageId="5" pageNumber="190" unit="mm" value="7.1">7.1 mm</quantity>
, ED: 
<quantity box="[611,707,531,555]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" pageId="5" pageNumber="190" unit="mm" value="0.29">0.29 mm</quantity>
, PL: 
<quantity box="[762,919,531,555]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.275" metricValueMax="2.32" metricValueMin="2.23" pageId="5" pageNumber="190" unit="mm" value="2.275" valueMax="2.32" valueMin="2.23">2.23–2.32 mm</quantity>
, PW: 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.175" metricValueMax="3.31" metricValueMin="3.04" pageId="5" pageNumber="190" unit="mm" value="3.175" valueMax="3.31" valueMin="3.04">3.04–3.31 mm</quantity>
, EW: 
<quantity box="[223,381,563,587]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.565" metricValueMax="3.65" metricValueMin="3.48" pageId="5" pageNumber="190" unit="mm" value="3.565" valueMax="3.65" valueMin="3.48">3.48–3.65 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5330008" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5330008" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5330008/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="190" startId="5.[113,152,1545,1564]" targetBox="[244,968,624,1523]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[113,1090,1545,1592]" pageId="5" pageNumber="190">
Figs. 13–16. 
<taxonomicName authority="Tang &amp; Li, 2012" authorityName="Tang &amp; Li" authorityYear="2012" box="[223,458,1546,1564]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Scaphidium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="190" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="bituberculatum" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[223,458,1546,1564]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="190">Scaphidium bituberculatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[462,528,1546,1565]" pageId="5" pageNumber="190" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
13 – aedeagus; 14 – internal sac; 15 – male front leg; 16 – antenna. Scale bars: 0.25 mm (13–14); 1 mm (15–16).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,219,1012]" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">Head with punctation clearly present only on posterior portion of frons, which is moderately coarse, dense and shallow. Pronotum distinctly elongate, strongly convex at base, antebasal puncture row deeply impressed, pronotal disc with punctation similar to that of posterior portion of frons. Elytron with two yellow spots: humeral spot strongly convex, subapical spot weakly convex. Lateral margin of elytron with prominent anterior subapical spot. Elytral disc with punctures moderately to very coarse and arranged to form irregular lines. Prohypomera uneven, with several scattered shallow punctures. Mesepisterna very sparsely and very shallowly punctate. Exposed abdominal tergites with coarse punctures and reticulate microsculpture. Ventrite I with coarse punctures restricted onto medio-basal portion, reticulate microsculpture covering its entire surface.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,219,1012]" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">
Male. Metaventrite with long pubescence covering nearly entire median portion. Profemora (
<figureCitation box="[159,233,571,596]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1545,1564]" captionTargetBox="[244,968,624,1523]" captionTargetId="figure-141@5.[228,972,612,1535]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 13–16. Scaphidium bituberculatum sp. nov. 13 – aedeagus; 14 – internal sac; 15 – male front leg; 16 – antenna. Scale bars: 0.25 mm (13–14); 1 mm (15–16)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5330008" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5330008/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) distinctly longer than those of female, inconspicuously tortuose on about half, ventral sides with row of small tubercles. Protibiae (
<figureCitation box="[634,712,603,628]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1545,1564]" captionTargetBox="[244,968,624,1523]" captionTargetId="figure-141@5.[228,972,612,1535]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 13–16. Scaphidium bituberculatum sp. nov. 13 – aedeagus; 14 – internal sac; 15 – male front leg; 16 – antenna. Scale bars: 0.25 mm (13–14); 1 mm (15–16)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5330008" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5330008/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) distinctly incurved, with two rows of small ventral tubercles.Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[515,589,636,660]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1545,1564]" captionTargetBox="[244,968,624,1523]" captionTargetId="figure-141@5.[228,972,612,1535]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 13–16. Scaphidium bituberculatum sp. nov. 13 – aedeagus; 14 – internal sac; 15 – male front leg; 16 – antenna. Scale bars: 0.25 mm (13–14); 1 mm (15–16)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5330008" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5330008/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
) with internal sac (
<figureCitation box="[787,861,636,660]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1545,1564]" captionTargetBox="[244,968,624,1523]" captionTargetId="figure-141@5.[228,972,612,1535]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 13–16. Scaphidium bituberculatum sp. nov. 13 – aedeagus; 14 – internal sac; 15 – male front leg; 16 – antenna. Scale bars: 0.25 mm (13–14); 1 mm (15–16)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5330008" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5330008/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) comprising longitudinal apical sclerite and complicated complex of basal sclerites which consists of several median sclerites and a pair of large and elongate lateral sclerites.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="191" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,219,1012]" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,403,731,755]" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Tang &amp; Li, 2012" authorityName="Tang &amp; Li" authorityYear="2012" box="[411,706,733,756]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Scaphidium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="191" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="bituberculatum" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[411,706,733,756]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">Scaphidium bituberculatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[714,799,732,755]" pageId="6" pageNumber="191" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Tang &amp; Li, 2010" authorityName="Tang &amp; Li" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Scaphidium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="191" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="direptum">
<emphasis box="[943,1066,733,756]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">S. direptum</emphasis>
Tang &amp; Li, 2010
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="TANG L. &amp; LI L. - Z." box="[282,468,763,788]" pageId="6" pageNumber="191" pagination="318 - 321" refId="ref2366" refString="TANG L. &amp; LI L. - Z. 2010 b: A new species of the genus Scaphidium Olivier from China (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Scaphidiinae). Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society 83: 318 - 321." type="journal article" year="2010">TANG &amp; LI 2010b</bibRefCitation>
) (
<figureCitation box="[490,589,763,788]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[113,152,1532,1551]" captionTargetBox="[177,1031,226,1504]" captionTargetId="figure-14@3.[158,1044,219,1517]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 5–8. Male habitus of Scaphidium Olivier, 1790. 5–6 – S. bituberculatum sp. nov., holotype; 7–8 – S. direptum Tang &amp; Li, 2010, paratype. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5330002" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5330002/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">Figs. 7, 8</figureCitation>
) from 
<collectingRegion box="[662,888,763,787]" country="China" name="Guangdong" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">Guangdong Province</collectingRegion>
due to the presence of prominent elytral spots. It may be easily distinguished from the latter species by its elongate pronotum, strongly convex elytral spots and different male sexual characters, in particular by the ventrally tuberculate profemora and protibiae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="191" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,219,1012]" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,280,892,916]" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is a combination of the Latin prefix 
<emphasis box="[901,931,893,916]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">bi-</emphasis>
and the adjective 
<emphasis box="[151,292,925,948]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">tuberculatum</emphasis>
, referring to its strongly prominent humeral spots.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,219,1012]" box="[151,357,955,979]" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,246,955,979]" pageId="6" pageNumber="191">Habitat.</emphasis>
Unknown
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
